President Donald J. Trump has declared a major disaster in the State of Alabama and has ordered Federal assistance to supplement recovery efforts in areas affected by severe storms, tornadoes, straight-line winds, and flooding from April 12 to April 13, 2020. The Federal funding will be available to State, tribal, and eligible local governments, as well as certain private nonprofit organizations, for emergency work and the repair or replacement of damaged facilities. The counties of Blount, Cullman, DeKalb, Etowah, Jackson, Marshall, and Walker are specifically included in the funding. Hazard mitigation measures statewide will also be eligible for cost-sharing funding. Terry L. Quarles has been appointed as the Federal Coordinating Officer for Federal recovery operations in the affected areas. Further designations may be made if requested by the State and warranted by additional damage assessments. For more information, media can contact the FEMA News Desk at (202) 646-3272 or FEMA-NEWS-DESK@FEMA.DHS.GOV.